body:
## 🐛 Bug Report

<!-- A clear and concise description of what the bug is. -->

Lib version: ^4.1.1

## Steps To Reproduce

<!-- The exact steps required to reproduce the issue, ideally with a code example -->

Loading files from buffers, reading a file from a stream, reading a file from a local file, writing a file using a stream, or writing a file using a stream, or writing a file, all result in the operations timing out, the files I'm trying to save are very small too, so I don't think that it is a memory issue. This happens using Windows 10 OS specifically in unit tests ran by jest, I can confirm this does not happen in Ubuntu 18 as well.

```typescript
  // From stream:
  async readFile(): Promise<void> {
    const readStream = this.createReadStream();
    await this.workbook.xlsx.read(readStream);
  }

  // From local file:
  async readFile(): Promise<void> {
    ...
    const tmpFileLocation = path.resolve(__dirname, 'tmp.xlsx');
    await this.workbook.xlsx.readFile(tmpFileLocation);
  }

...

  async writeFile(): Promise<void> {
    const { workbook, outputFile } = this;

    // If the output file path is a valid S3 URI, write to S3:
    if (isS3) {
      const s3 = getS3Instance(outputFile);
      const s3Location = getS3Location(outputFile);
      const stream = new PassThrough();

      await workbook.xlsx.write(stream);

      await s3.upload({
        Key: s3Location.key,
        Bucket: s3Location.bucket,
        Body: stream,
        ContentType: 'application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet',
        ACL: 'bucket-owner-full-control'
      }).promise();
    } else {
      // Otherwise, write local file:
      const oFile = getFileAbsolutePath(outputFile);
      await workbook.xlsx.writeFile(oFile);
    }
  }
```

## The expected behavior:

Well, to the files to be read or written of course! Any ideas? Thanks in advance.
